Introduction

The Academy Awards, as known as the Oscars, is one of the most prestigious and significant awards in the entertainment industry. Among more than twenty Award of Merit categories, the nomination of Best Actors, Best Actress, Best Supporting Actors and Best Supporting Actress are highly anticipated by audience around the world.

Purpose of the exploration

This project is focused on actors and actress nominated by Oscars for their performances in the last fifty years from 1972. Datasets used in the analysis are adapted from IMDb and Oscar nominations and filmographies since 1972, which will be processed into two new datasets.

The analysis will be guided by the following prompts: - Explore number of Oscar nominations and wins for each actor/actress. - Explore the age when actors/actresses won Oscars Award or was nominated by Oscars. - Explore the reputation of nominated actors/actresses by analyzing ratings of the films they are playing roles in. - Cross-datasets analysis is also used to explore the relationship between variables in the two datasets.

Process Datasets

Description of the source of raw datasets

The major and the most important datasets in this project are provided by IMDb (IMDb Data Files Available for Download). There are 7 datasets available and I will only choose 4 of them and join them together.

To aid my analysis, I also incorporate the dataset nomination_stats contributed by milanjanosov on Kaggle. The convenience of this dataset is that it use the same unique identifier for films (tconst) and actresses/actors (nconst) as IMDb.

Tidy and join datasets

I performed several filtering and joining steps to reduce the size of the datasets so it only contains information that will be used in my analysis.

Code 
#Combining IMDb datasets
movie_full<- title %>% 
  #First filter the dataset and maintain only movie related rows
  filter(title_type == "movie") %>% 
  #Then join with other datasets by unique identifiers
  inner_join(principals, by = "tconst") %>% 
  inner_join(name_doc, by = "nconst") %>% 
  left_join(ratings, by = "tconst")

After combining the IMDb datasets and store it as movie_full, I merged it with nomination_stats and obtained two final datasets: - nominees_and_winners: this dataset includes basic information for each yearâs nomination of Oscars Award. - nominees_rating: this dataset is obtained by joining the IMDb datasets and the nomination datasets, which includes all the ratings for films that each Oscars nominees once played a role in.

Code 
nominees_and_winners<- movie_full %>% 
  arrange(nconst) %>% 
  distinct(nconst, birth_year) %>% 
  right_join(nomination_stats, c("nconst" = "name_id")) %>% 
  arrange(year) %>% 
  select(year, category, name, nconst, birth_year, outcome)

nominees_rating <- nominees_and_winners %>% 
  distinct(nconst, name) %>% 
  inner_join(movie_full, "nconst") %>% 
  select(name, nconst, primary_title, tconst, average_rating, start_year)

Discussion of NA values

To check for NA values, I also defined a helper function get_NA() that will return a tibble with rows where any NA occurs.

Code 
# Defining function
get_NA <- function (df){
  colnms <- colnames (df)
  df %>% 
    filter_at(vars(all_of(colnms)), any_vars(is.na(.)))
}

Distribution of the nomineeâs age

In this section, I will explore the distribution of the age of Oscars nominees (including winners), particularly the age when they first won or were first nominated.

To analyze the data efficiently, I defined three helper functions combining with iteration:

Code 
# To calculate the age when the artist is nominated or wins
calc_age <- function (df){
  df %>% 
    mutate(age = .$year - .$birth_year)
}

# # To find the oldest nominees/winners using iteration
# max_age <- function(df){
#   output <- 0
#   for (i in seq_along(df$age)){
#      while (df$age[[i]] > output){
#        output <- df$age[[i]]
#      }
#   }
#   output
# }

#To find the youngest nominees/winners using iteration
min_age <- function(df){
  output <- df$age[[1]]
  for (i in seq_along(df$age)){
    while (output > df$age[[i]]){
      output <- df$age[[i]]
    }
  }
  output
}

Then, I use the min_age() function to find the age when the artist first wins or is nominated by Oscars Awards. The results are saved in two datasets:

Code 
# The age of artists when they are first nominated
age_first_nominated <-
  nominees %>% 
  calc_age() %>% 
  split(.$name) %>% 
  map_dbl(min_age) %>% 
  enframe() %>% 
  rename("age" = "value")

# The age of artists when they first win the award
age_first_win <-
  winners %>% 
  calc_age() %>% 
  split(.$name) %>% 
  map_dbl(min_age) %>% 
  enframe() %>% 
  rename("age" = "value")

The Oscars Awards and the rating

In this section, I will implement cross-dataset analysis to explore factors that influence the rating.

Relationship between the amount of wins or nominations and ratings artists receive

It is possible that there will be an relationship between the amount of wins or nominations received by an artists and the ratings they receive.

Code 
# Correlation between the number of nominations and ratings 
reputation %>% 
  inner_join(select(nomination_times, n, nconst), by = "nconst") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ratings, y = n, group = n))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title = "Number of nominations vs Ratings",
    y = "Number of nominations")

By comparing the number of nominations and the distribution of ratings corresponding to each category of nomination amount, we can observe a trend that as the number of nominations increases, ratings in general will also increases. But there are outliers like Meryl Streep who has 21 nominations but has a rating of 6.63 and Jack Nicholson with 10 nominations but has rating of 6.38.

Code 
# Correlation between number of wins and reputation

reputation %>% 
  inner_join(select(win_times, nconst, n), by = "nconst") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ratings, y = n, group = n))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title = "Number of nominations vs Ratings",
    y = "Number of nominations")

The relationship between the number of wins and ratings of artists has similar characteristics to the relationship between the number of nominations and ratings. As the number of wins increases, the ratings will also increases. The difference is that the medians of ratings have larger range in the in nominated artists than in winners, in terms of both lowest median and the highest median. It might because thereâs larger amount of nominees, which leads to larger variations in data. But another explanation can be that the winning an Oscars Award doesnât define the quality of performance and audiencesâ perception of the artists. It is possible that a high-skilled actors/actress has never won an Oscars Award. For example, Quinn Cummings has the highest rating, best has never won Oscars Awards.

The positive correlation shown in the two graphs here might indicate that Oscarsâs voting membersâ perception of artists is in accordance with the audienceâs perception of artists. It is possible that the result of Oscars Awards will influence audiences expectations and perceptions of the film, or the publicâs perception of a film will influence voting memberâs decision. However, whether there is a causality between the two is not clear.

Relationship between the age and the ratings

People usually link the age when a person reveal a certain level of extraordinary characteristics to the talent that person has in the specific field. Usually, the younger the age, the more talented this person is. In the context of entertainment industry, the specialty of an actor/actress is signaled by winning or nominated by an prestigious award like the Oscars Awards.

To investigate whether the linkage is reasonable or true to the entertainment industry, I will explore the relationship between the age when artists first win or are nominated by the Oscars and the their ratings. Here winning an award or being nominated represent their extraordinary specialties and the ratings represent their talents perceived by the audience.

Code 
# Combine the nominees dataset with the nominees_rating dataset 
reputation %>% 
  inner_join(age_first_nominated, by = "name") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = ratings)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title = "The age when being nominated vs Ratings")

From the plot showing the relationship between the age when nominated and ratings, thereâs no clear trend can be summarized. When looking specifically at the age group below 25, ratings are sparsely distributed in the range between 5.25 and 7.50. When looking at the age above 75, ratings are distributed between 7.0 and 5.75, which has smaller variation. Observation of this plot doesnât support the claim the younger the more talented.

However, there is a possibility that winning an award has a more decisive role in determining an artistâs extraordinarity. Thus, the exploration between the age when artists first win the Oscars Awards and their ratings is needed.

Code 
# Combine the winners dataset with the nominees_rating dataset 
reputation %>% 
  inner_join(age_first_win, by = "name") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = ratings)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title = "The age when becoming an winner vs Ratings")

The relationship between the age becoming an Oscars winners and the ratings is generally weak, while a positive correlation between the age and ratings can be found in the age group below 40. Nonetheless, this trend contradicts to the intuition of the public, as to prove the publicâs hypothesis there should be a negative correlation between the age and the ratings.

Therefore, data in my datasets doesnât support peopleâs intuition âthe younger the more talentedâ. Individuals born as performers or other talents might only be rare occasions, while most of the people need exercise and experience to improve their skills. There is also a possibility that individuals reveal their talents at a young age but the talent is just a flash in the pan.

Conclusion

From 1972 to 2022, there are 556 artists were once nominated as Best Actors, Best Actress, Best Supporting Actors and Best Supporting Actress due to their impressive performances in the film. Among them, 172 artists won Oscars Awards in the intense competition. While most of the artists were only able to be nominated or won the award once, there are artists with multiple statues or becoming Oscars nominees several times. But still, those artists account for a very small portion of the total nomineesâ population.

In addition, I also investigate the age distribution of Oscars winners and nominees. The age here refers to the age when they are first nominated or win an award. A scenario can be drawn is that most artists have an achievement from their 30s to 50s, whereas winning an award occurs later in the artistâs career compared to receiving an nomination. Anomalies are Justin Henry and Gloria Stuart who were first nominated at an age of 9 and 88 respectively, and Tatum OâNeal and Christopher Plummer who won the award at an age of 11 and 83 respectively.

The potential relationship between whether or not an actor/actress has Oscars nominations and their reputation of performance is also examined in this EDA. It turns out that nearly 75% of Oscars nominees have ratings above 6.12, indicating that broadly speaking they have better reputation among audiences if to say an average reputation is the rating of 5.00.

One might be curious about the disparity between Oscars voting membersâ preference and the general publicâs preference. In the section âThe Oscars Awards and the ratingâ, I analyzed the relationship between the number of nominations or wins and the ratings of artists. The result shows that there is certain level of consistency in voting membersâ and the general publicâs evaluation of artistsâ performancesâthe more the artists receive nominations or win, the higher the ratings. But the Oscars Awards isnât all, artists with highest ratings might not be the same group of persons with most nominations and wins. Besides, I also use my datasets to examine peopleâs belief in talented persons will reveal their talents at a very young age. Nevertheless, my datasets doesnât support this claim. Discovering, exhibiting and maintaining talents will be influenced by various factors when a person grows up and in their career, the age may not be the best perspective to evalueate oneâs talent.
